# RevivifAI — Professional TypeScript Standards

## Language baseline

Target **TypeScript 6.x** or as declared in `tsconfig.json`. Prefer features and idioms that are correct for that version.

When unsure, treat these as authoritative:

- [TypeScript Handbook](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/)
- [TypeScript 6.0 Release Notes](https://devblogs.microsoft.com/typescript/announcing-typescript-6-0/)
- [TypeScript 5.0 Release Notes](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/release-notes/typescript-5-0.html)
- [TypeScript 5.2 Release Notes](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/release-notes/typescript-5-2.html)

Project automation (ESLint, Prettier) in configuration files is the source of truth for enforced rules; align new code with those settings.

## Array indexing

Prefer `.at()` for accessing array elements by index, especially when the index may be out of bounds or comes from a variable. The `.at()` method:

- Returns `undefined` for out-of-bounds indices instead of creating a hole or accessing prototype
- Supports negative indices for accessing from the end
- Avoids triggering `security/detect-object-injection` ESLint rules
- Is idiomatic and self-documenting

```typescript
// BAD — bracket notation can trigger security warnings and prototype pollution
const first = arr[0];
const last = arr[arr.length - 1];
const item = arr[index];

// GOOD — .at() is safe, idiomatic, and handles bounds gracefully
const first = arr.at(0);
const last = arr.at(-1);
const item = arr.at(index);
```

Use bracket notation only when:

- The index is a literal number and the array length is known (e.g., tuple destructuring)
- Performance is critical in a hot loop and bounds are guaranteed

```typescript
// ACCEPTABLE — literal index on a known-length tuple
const [a, b] = pair;
const point = coordinates[0]; // where coordinates is [number, number, number]
```

## Types and interfaces

- Prefer `interface` for object shapes that may be extended.
- Prefer `type` for unions, intersections, and mapped types.
- Use `readonly` for immutable arrays and objects.
- Avoid `any`; use `unknown` when the type is truly unknown and narrow with type guards.

## Imports

- Use named imports preferentially.
- Use `import type` for type-only imports to avoid runtime overhead.
- Group imports logically: built-ins, external packages, internal modules.
